I fell pray to massive cognitive bias on this market. All the way from September - December I was (accurately) predicting a large winter wave leading to >12k hospitalizations in this bracket. Then Omicron somehow convinced me to throw out that logic, because a country in the middle of summer (South Africa) was doing well and I wanted to believe that was a good sign. Then discussion with other players on this market who were correctly predicting an Omicron wave of hospitalizations just caused me to reactively dig in further on the optimistic side, rather than listen closely to them and to my own former argument in favor of a seasonal wave. 14-day average of hospitalized patients at 5009 on Jan 2, 7 days after 51.5 cases/100k population on Dec 26. Hospitalizations lag cases by approx 7-10 days, so estimating the number hospitalized as a fraction of cases 7 days ago will underestimate hospitalizations as a fraction of cases. So 5009/51.5 = 97.3 is an underestimate of hospitalizations per 1 case/100k population. 12000 / 97.3 = 123 cases per 100k population; thus, if CA sees 123 cases per 100k population, a 14-day average of 12k hospitalizations is all but assured. Moreover, in addition to this being an underestimate based on assuming 7 days between cases and hospitalizations, it's also likely an underestimate because cases to date have been skewed towards younger segments of the population. Because US cases are currently 1.6x last year's peak but have not yet peaked, I don't see how CA can escape seeing more than 123 cases per 100k population = 1.1x last year's peak and hence a 14-day average of 12k hospitalizations. And I don't see how this won't happen before Feb 1, as cases are soaring and will likely reach a 7-day average of 123 per 100k population in about 1 week. And I can't imagine hospital capacity precluding 12k being reached, because >22k was reached last year. I'm still trying to force myself to be at least a little cautious in this forecast, but my real instinct is to put this forecast at 99%. It's almost done, imo. 14-day average of hospitalizations at 4137 on Dec 28. 7-day average of cases/day at about 30 per 100k population on Dec 21. Assume hospitalizations lag cases by at least 7 days. Base on England's experience so far, it's likely that the 7-day average of cases/day will peak at more than double last winter's peak of ~109 per 100k population. So if the hospital census at 30/100k is 4137, and if cases do reach double last year's cases, then it would not be unreasonable to expect the peak number hospitalized to reach at least 4137 / 30 * 109 * 2 = 30k. Will cases rise so high? I don't know, but I don't see why CA should be so special as to escape at least very high cases. And I do think it will happen very soon, perhaps within a couple weeks. As hospitalizations generally lag case by 7-10 days, I think a peak in hospitalizations should be reached in late January, possibly early February. Last year, the 7-day average of hospitalizations peaked on Jan 14, and cases peaked January 9 (at the tail end of a data reporting issue, so the actual peak could have been a couple days earlier). I think it's reasonable to expect Omicron cases to peak by mid Jan at the latest and then hospitalizations to peak most likely in the 2nd half of January. There's a lot of uncertainty in my mind about how high hospitalizations will go, but somewhere in the range 12k-30k+ seems possible to me.

Things aren't adding up. Initial estimates of R0 for Omicron made it look almost as contagious as measles. However, for this calculation, it was assumed that the serial interval (time between cases in a chain of transmission) is the same for Delta and Omicron. However, evidence is mounting that the serial interval for Omicron is actually shorter (~3d) for Omicron than that of Delta (~4.3d): https://twitter.com/trvrb/status/1474143598476083201 That means that R0 for Omicron will be lower than initial estimates, which is good for humanity. It also means that the peak of the wave will be lower and earlier than previously anticipated. Indeed, the fact that SA cases peaked early and fairly low compared to what one would have expected with an R0 almost as high as that of measles is what made me wonder about this possibility. It appears that London cases may already have peaked, too.

https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/22/health/covid-omicron-delta-hospitalizations.html South Africa and Scotland find 70% reduction in actual hospital admissions. Imperial finds 20% reduction because they measured anyone walking into a hospital rather than people getting admitted and given a bed, which is what we care about for this question.

New Imperial College report out looking at hospitalizations in England. There's enough data this week to make preliminary estimates of the relative risk of hospitalization with Omicron vs. Delta: "Table 2 shows the hazard ratio (HR) for hospitalisation for Omicron vs Delta cases and for reinfections vs primary infections computed over all vaccination categories, for five data subsets. Estimates, uncorrected for under ascertainment of reinfection status, show that Omicron cases have a 15-20% reduced risk of any hospitalisation and a 41% (95% CI: 37%-45%) reduced risk of a hospitalisation resulting in a stay of 1 or more nights. Reinfection is associated with approximately a 50-60% reduction in hospitalisation risk compared with primary infections. However, assuming only 33% of true reinfections are identified as such, corrected estimates suggest lower reduction in Omicron hospitalisation compared with Delta (ranging from approximately 0-30% depending on the data subset), and a higher reduction in the risk of hospitalisation associated with reinfection (of approximately 55-70%)." https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/mrc-gida/2021-12-22-COVID19-Report-50.pdf

Despite The WHO’s December 17th Technical Brief on the Omicron variant, South Africa is still the strongest model of future outcomes. South African appears to have passed its peak in hospitalizations and reports are that hospitalizations are 18-30% lower than Delta. This percentage alone would cause me to think it’s unlikely that the 14 day average hospitalization rate in California will reach 12,000. However, there are still a lot of conflicting variables that still make this a potential toss-up for me:

~15k new cases as of 20 Dec '21 and rising, 7d-average at ~7.5k with a slope slowly turning upwards. Despite intense testing, the wave is getting more inertia in California, which speaks for a high omicron share. The dark field in CA is small, which speaks for an early hospitalization in the process if necessary. With a time lag of 7 to 12 days, the number of hospitalizations is going to catch up average case counts. There will be 35 more days to double afterwards, which shouldn't be too difficult for omicron, even if the average symptoms are milder.

Cases in S.A. have peaked at about 17.5% above the previous delta peak (https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus/country/south-africa). Estimates tending to put hospitalization/case for omicron at least 70% relative to delta. Combined, we might expect hospitalization to be about 82% of the previous peak of 22k = 18k. Exacerbating this is the fact that it is winter in California but summer in S.A., and that California's population is older than S.A.. Mitigating it is the fact that California's vax rate is 2-3x as high, and that omicron hospital stays are discharged faster than in previous waves.
Slight step to just above a consensus aid and below my previous forecast. Current forecast lies in between these two.

This is certainly looking much more likely to happen before 31st January than it did a few weeks ago, but not yet a certainty imo (although that could change in a matter of days). During the Delta wave it took 50 days for hospitalisation to climb 7k and peak at over 8.5k on the 14-day average. In the current Omicron wave it would need to climb 8k within 35 days. So roughly 14% higher and 60% faster. The main uncertainty for me is not whether it will happen (I think it will) but whether it will be a few days earlier or later than 31st Jan. If hospitalised cases involve lengthy stays and cases climb very quickly, then it looks like the last week of Jan will be met, but a slower rise and shorter stays should smooth the curve and delay the peak a week or so. It now seems established that full vaccination plus a booster is the only way to maintain significant immunity against Omicron. California opened boosters to all residents in mid-November after prioritising the elderly for 2 months, but uptake has actually been better among younger age groups, and generally far lower than hoped and expected (something like 15-20%). So as a generalisation the more elderly with lower immunity are now more likely to need longer hospitalisation. Comparing with Canada's current situation of escalating cases within the context of much higher vaccination levels (76.2% of total population full dosed, compared to 67.4% in California), and increasing booster uptake, the speed of hospitalisation in California could change very rapidly. Median age may be a few years younger in California (36.5 against 40.1 in Ontario for example), but the lower immunity is perhaps more critical. Mask wearing is mandated but California has quite diverse mix of communities, vax rates, and health, so the key probably lies with factoring the speed of spread with age, immunity, and length of hospitalisation. I'll refine the forecast over next few days.

Sometimes, it feels like my brain takes a long time to make a turn. Inertia is a powerful thing. Let me try to shake off all of my previous thinking and look anew. If someone showed me the graphs of cases and hospitalizations for CA and told me it was for, say, some province in Canada, a completely new question, what would I think? I would think, Omicron is coming. The wave will be higher than last year's winter wave. It will likely peak around the third week in January nationally. It will peak in different places at different times, but Omicron is so contagious that it likely won't peak anywhere in "Canada" later than the first week of Feb or so. Aside from the question of when cases will peak, with exponential case growth, even if slowed a bit with some mitigations, cases will get really high in January. I can't imagine it going otherwise. I could easily imagine 80 cases/100k population by Jan 21, and I can't easily imagine how that wouldn't lead to 12k+ hospitalizations by the end of January. There is, of course, a huge amount of uncertainty here.

I'm not sure when exactly Omicron will hit California. I'm expecting a national peak in cases around the third week in January; CA cases could peak before or after that. Hospitalizations lag cases by 1 week, of course. Also, what level of Omicron cases will correspond to 12k hospitalizations? Too many unknowns right now. But I do expect CA's peak to be much higher than its Delta peak because 1) Omicron is more contagious, 2) it will be winter, and 3) the population has very little immunity. But looking at this more closely, I don't see how Omicron cases won't reach ~50 cases/100k population, which, if this were Delta, would correspond to ~12k hospitalizations. And cases will likely go far higher than that, so that even if Omicron does end up having a lower hospitalization rate than Delta because of prior immunity, it'll still end up causing more hospitalizations. It's hard to picture this many hospitalizations from here, but it's starting to look likely to me.

Made my original estimate a week ago, so updating for new data. The hospitalization trend continues to look exponential, and therefore points to a pre-15SEP21 breach of the 12000 number. I realized that hospitalizations is a LAGGING indicator though, and that I should rely on the leading indicators: # tests; confirmed cases; and positivity rate (although the hospitalization numbers are available on a 1 day lag while these other indicators are on a 1 week lag, so there is still some effort to align the time periods). 1) 7 day average positive test rate per 100k increased 25% over the past week, which would mean we'll breach 12000 even earlier than my original estimate of 02SEP1. 2) 7 day average case rate per 100k is stable at 25. 3) Positivity rate is down from 7.1% of all tests to 6.5% over the last few days, but that's still more than enough to reach 12000 before 02SEP21 (and it may just be a data quality issue). 4) # of total tests looks exponential.
